And that's your job, right?

234
00:09:32,557 --> 00:09:34,179
Like, you're enjoying that because it's kind of cool.

235
00:09:34,179 --> 00:09:36,060
You get all the information, you know what's design doing,

236
00:09:36,060 --> 00:09:37,001
you know what's code doing.

237
00:09:37,001 --> 00:09:38,423
Like, you're talking to the head of studio

238
00:09:38,423 --> 00:09:39,784
and every now and then you meet the CEO

239
00:09:39,784 --> 00:09:40,865
and like, that's kind of fun.

240
00:09:40,865 --> 00:09:45,309
And you see way further than anyone else in your team

241
00:09:45,309 --> 00:09:46,270
and that's your job.

242
00:09:46,270 --> 00:09:49,093
And then, especially when you used to be an artist,

243
00:09:49,093 --> 00:09:49,953
a problem pops up.

244
00:09:50,778 --> 00:09:52,900
And you go like, whoa, problem, that's my thing,

245
00:09:52,900 --> 00:09:54,422
I'm an artist, I'm solving problems,

246
00:09:54,422 --> 00:09:55,784
that's what I did the last 10 years,

247
00:09:55,784 --> 00:09:57,746
so there we go, I'm solving the problem.

248
00:09:57,746 --> 00:10:00,309
And while you're solving that problem,

249
00:10:00,309 --> 00:10:04,174
the dude who's supposed to keep the overview is not there.

250
00:10:04,174 --> 00:10:05,155
And things get worse.

251
00:10:05,155 --> 00:10:07,718
And you go back, and there we go, imposter syndrome.

252
00:10:07,718 --> 00:10:08,459
I have no idea what I'm doing.

253
00:10:09,894 --> 00:10:13,538
And this is so simple, but it's so straightforward.

254
00:10:13,538 --> 00:10:15,520
It's micromanagement and delegation.

255
00:10:15,520 --> 00:10:18,983
Like I guarantee everybody of you have like cursed their lead

256
00:10:18,983 --> 00:10:20,745
or their director or like whoever is superior

257
00:10:20,745 --> 00:10:22,147
that like he doesn't know what he's doing

258
00:10:22,147 --> 00:10:23,188
and he's not in control of that

259
00:10:23,188 --> 00:10:25,750
and why is he micromanaging me?

260
00:10:25,750 --> 00:10:27,732
But it's so difficult in nature

261
00:10:27,732 --> 00:10:30,035
because when you move into leadership.

262
00:10:31,173 --> 00:10:34,156
The thing you've been doing till then is the exact opposite.

263
00:10:34,156 --> 00:10:36,257
So it's in your human nature to act like this.

264
00:10:36,257 --> 00:10:37,979
And making sure you're not doing this

265
00:10:37,979 --> 00:10:39,620
is something that has to run constantly

266
00:10:39,620 --> 00:10:40,901
in the back of your mind.

267
00:10:40,901 --> 00:10:43,683
And it's sneaky, because you never realize

268
00:10:43,683 --> 00:10:44,623
you're actually doing it.

269
00:10:44,623 --> 00:10:46,825
Because it is something that is nature to you,

270
00:10:46,825 --> 00:10:48,406
so you have to kind of get rid of it.

271
00:10:48,406 --> 00:10:50,568
And at the same time, you can't get rid of something

272
00:10:50,568 --> 00:10:52,709
that you have nurtured for decades.

273
00:10:53,110 --> 00:10:58,754
So the thing that you realize at that point is I have leads, I have artists.

274
00:10:58,754 --> 00:11:04,218
Those guys are the people who will take care of that, like who won't like.

275
00:11:04,218 --> 00:11:04,998
It's their job now.

276
00:11:04,998 --> 00:11:07,020
Like you're the guy who has the overview

277
00:11:07,020 --> 00:11:10,002
and your leads will make sure that whatever is going on there.

278
00:11:11,060 --> 00:11:11,740
will be handled.

279
00:11:11,740 --> 00:11:14,042
And the beauty of it, and that's a big realization for me,

280
00:11:14,042 --> 00:11:18,724
was your leads don't, like you're hiring to your weaknesses.

281
00:11:18,724 --> 00:11:20,806
You're getting the people who are way better

282
00:11:20,806 --> 00:11:21,906
at stuff you have no clue about.

283
00:11:21,906 --> 00:11:24,588
So one person sitting back there,

284
00:11:24,588 --> 00:11:27,230
she got precisely hired for the fact that I'm chaotic

285
00:11:27,230 --> 00:11:30,512
and I'm nervous, and she's calm and very organized.

286
00:11:30,512 --> 00:11:32,073
And my boss was smart enough to do that.

287
00:11:32,073 --> 00:11:34,294
And once I realized that, a whole world opened up

288
00:11:34,294 --> 00:11:36,936
because I realized, well, I have no clue about animation.

289
00:11:36,936 --> 00:11:38,877
Maybe we should hire someone who's really good at that.

290
00:11:39,462 --> 00:11:41,444
And we did that, and he took care of the pipeline,

291
00:11:41,444 --> 00:11:42,925
and we met every now and then, and he told me,

292
00:11:42,925 --> 00:11:43,865
this is what we're doing.

293
00:11:43,865 --> 00:11:45,826
And I'm like, yeah, that works with what we're having

294
00:11:45,826 --> 00:11:47,007
in plan, keep going.

295
00:11:47,007 --> 00:11:50,129
And that's amazing, because then you have a group of people

296
00:11:50,129 --> 00:11:52,331
who are totally specialized in what they're doing,

297
00:11:52,331 --> 00:11:54,472
they're way better at what you do, and guess what?

298
00:11:54,472 --> 00:11:56,473
The imposter syndrome just slightly gets away

299
00:11:56,473 --> 00:11:58,395
because you figured out, I don't have to know

300
00:11:58,395 --> 00:12:00,976
all that crazy stuff I have no clue about.

301
00:12:00,976 --> 00:12:02,497
And so over time, you're calming down,

302
00:12:02,497 --> 00:12:06,000
and you realize giving ownership to people is a big deal.

303
00:12:06,965 --> 00:12:08,726
because it makes people motivated.

304
00:12:08,726 --> 00:12:12,467
It's that one thing that people make them stay longer,

305
00:12:12,467 --> 00:12:14,327
which I'm German, we're all about efficiency

306
00:12:14,327 --> 00:12:15,808
and time efficiency and all that kind of stuff.

307
00:12:15,808 --> 00:12:18,448
So it sounds nice, but it's kind of evil

308
00:12:18,448 --> 00:12:21,129
where you go like, you own this, this is yours,

309
00:12:21,129 --> 00:12:22,670
but you have to take care of this, right?

310
00:12:22,670 --> 00:12:24,950
And because you own it and you take pride in that.

311
00:12:25,443 --> 00:12:29,724
you take care of it. You stay longer. You might come in a weekend or two. I don't know about it.

312
00:12:29,724 --> 00:12:33,705
I don't care. It's good. So it's a nasty thing, but at the same time, it's a great thing because

313
00:12:33,705 --> 00:12:38,746
people actually enjoy doing it. And it doesn't matter at that point because you're having fun.

314
00:12:38,746 --> 00:12:45,647
Like you're owning that. And so with that in mind, you're realizing, okay, I have to give people

315
00:12:45,647 --> 00:12:49,668
ownership over the stuff they're working on, but I still need to direct them because I have the

316
00:12:49,668 --> 00:12:51,348
overview. I need to figure out.

317
00:12:52,721 --> 00:12:55,683
how to make them build the things I need

318
00:12:55,683 --> 00:12:58,465
without taking and stifling their creativity, right?

319
00:12:58,465 --> 00:13:01,186
So you're standing there and you're starting to figure out,

320
00:13:01,186 --> 00:13:02,007
like, how can I do that?

321
00:13:02,007 --> 00:13:04,128
How can I give them very clear direction?

322
00:13:04,128 --> 00:13:05,569
Because this is what it boils down to.

323
00:13:05,569 --> 00:13:09,912
And I've seen it go south both ways,

324
00:13:09,912 --> 00:13:11,893
where one way is where people hone in

325
00:13:11,893 --> 00:13:13,754
and give like very, very detailed feedback.

326
00:13:13,754 --> 00:13:15,875
And then the other one is where they get

327
00:13:15,875 --> 00:13:17,296
like very abstract feedback.

328
00:13:17,296 --> 00:13:19,578
And we call it the fazoozle.

329
00:13:20,335 --> 00:13:22,855
And there's tons of versions where you go like,

330
00:13:22,855 --> 00:13:24,455
okay, this doesn't have enough punch.

331
00:13:24,455 --> 00:13:26,096
There isn't enough jazz in it.

332
00:13:26,096 --> 00:13:27,816
Or like, there are terms you can't believe.

333
00:13:27,816 --> 00:13:28,836
Like, it's crazy.

334
00:13:28,836 --> 00:13:31,457
And the thing is, it's really bad

335
00:13:31,457 --> 00:13:33,837
because people don't know what you're asking them.

336
00:13:33,837 --> 00:13:35,598
Like, they don't understand what you want to go for,

337
00:13:35,598 --> 00:13:36,838
but you're not doing it on purpose

338
00:13:36,838 --> 00:13:38,078
because you just want to make sure

339
00:13:38,078 --> 00:13:39,798
that they can do what they want.

340
00:13:39,798 --> 00:13:43,259
So it's almost like an art form to figure out

341
00:13:43,259 --> 00:13:46,500
how can I get someone to do what we need

342
00:13:46,500 --> 00:13:48,300
without taking away all the creativity

343
00:13:48,300 --> 00:13:49,640
and like ownership out of them.

344
00:13:50,280 --> 00:13:53,702
And in my experience, the best metaphor I have for that

345
00:13:53,702 --> 00:13:56,923
is this, where you go like, it's somewhere in this location,

346
00:13:56,923 --> 00:13:59,984
which could be the briefing you have from creative.

347
00:13:59,984 --> 00:14:02,065
It's somehow something like that, in that case,

348
00:14:02,065 --> 00:14:05,526
like we need a ship to get here, but figure it out yourself.

349
00:14:05,526 --> 00:14:08,887
And I just talked to an art director a couple of weeks ago,

350
00:14:08,887 --> 00:14:10,328
and he said something really smart to me.

351
00:14:10,328 --> 00:14:12,829
It's like directors give direction, never solutions.

352
00:14:12,829 --> 00:14:15,130
And I think that's the nature of it.

353
00:14:15,130 --> 00:14:17,110
So, and that comes with it.

354
00:14:17,110 --> 00:14:18,771
What makes it hard again is,

355
00:14:19,233 --> 00:14:23,474
whatever you had in mind won't be the thing they're going to build.

356
00:14:23,474 --> 00:14:25,435
The thing they're going to build will be something else.

357
00:14:25,435 --> 00:14:31,397
It will fit the criteria, but it won't be what you imagine it's supposed to be.

358
00:14:31,397 --> 00:14:34,318
But the beauty of that is the only person who knows that is you.

359
00:14:35,129 --> 00:14:36,811
when the player is going to play the game,

360
00:14:36,811 --> 00:14:39,014
the consumers see it and it fits, it fits.

361
00:14:39,014 --> 00:14:41,316
Like the only person who has to be cool with it is yourself.

362
00:14:41,316 --> 00:14:43,539
But obviously, because you used to be an artist

363
00:14:43,539 --> 00:14:46,202
and you had like a very small thing in mind

364
00:14:46,202 --> 00:14:47,844
and you always had 100% control,

365
00:14:47,844 --> 00:14:49,806
it's very, very, very hard to let go of that

366
00:14:49,806 --> 00:14:53,110
because it is not in your nature.

367
00:14:53,928 --> 00:14:57,732
And so having this team, having this group working on stuff

368
00:14:57,732 --> 00:15:00,915
that you have no control on, and at the same time

369
00:15:00,915 --> 00:15:03,458
trying making that navigate, you will suffer with that.

370
00:15:03,458 --> 00:15:06,101
You will try so many things and it won't work out

371
00:15:06,101 --> 00:15:07,543
in the beginning, and it's totally fine

372
00:15:07,543 --> 00:15:08,904
because you're learning that.

373
00:15:08,904 --> 00:15:10,706
Like this is actual art direction.

374
00:15:10,706 --> 00:15:12,969
Like this part to me was the most.

375
00:15:13,469 --> 00:15:19,932
That's the nature of making art direction, because you're directing people to a point without telling them what to do.

376
00:15:19,932 --> 00:15:22,994
And the only way to learn that is try and error.

377
00:15:22,994 --> 00:15:24,635
There is no magic bullet for that.

378
00:15:24,635 --> 00:15:28,296
And you will suffer, I promise.

379
00:15:28,296 --> 00:15:35,060
So, with that in mind, you realize you need to know your team, you need to know the group you're working with.

380
00:15:36,280 --> 00:15:39,503
because that sort of feedback is very, very personal.

381
00:15:39,503 --> 00:15:42,727
So one person would need a specific set of words

382
00:15:42,727 --> 00:15:44,810
and sentences that triggers them to do that.

383
00:15:44,810 --> 00:15:47,373
Some people would very badly react to that.

384
00:15:47,373 --> 00:15:51,297
So you have to figure out who reacts to what, what way.

385
00:15:51,297 --> 00:15:52,579
So you start getting to know your team

386
00:15:52,579 --> 00:15:54,561
and that's something which is.

387
00:15:54,801 --> 00:15:57,802
super difficult because as I mentioned you're the guy who has the overview.

388
00:15:57,802 --> 00:16:02,844
Like you're the person who actually deliberately tries to stay back to keep everything working.

389
00:16:02,844 --> 00:16:06,606
And it's very easy because you spend a lot of time in meetings, Jesus Christ,

390
00:16:06,606 --> 00:16:12,688
a lot of time in meetings. And you'll have like these small intermingling five minutes in between

391
00:16:12,688 --> 00:16:16,590
meetings where you meet people. And if you don't maintain the relationship to the artists you work

392
00:16:16,590 --> 00:16:21,092
with and when your director, the leads you work with, and you don't understand them on a personal level

393
00:16:21,332 --> 00:16:22,732
it will make things worse.

394
00:16:22,732 --> 00:16:27,114
And so it is super important that you understand your team dynamics,

395
00:16:27,114 --> 00:16:29,816
you understand how your team is built up, how it works,

396
00:16:29,816 --> 00:16:32,437
how they kind of communicate with each other.

397
00:16:32,437 --> 00:16:35,899
And so when that happens,

398
00:16:35,899 --> 00:16:40,501
you look into that moment where, how do you say,

399
00:16:40,501 --> 00:16:43,763
you understand the person, you pinpoint them.

400
00:16:46,328 --> 00:16:49,189
I messed up my presentation, sorry.

401
00:16:49,189 --> 00:16:52,511
Imposter syndrome, there we go.

402
00:16:52,511 --> 00:16:54,733
So you work with that, you work with people,

403
00:16:54,733 --> 00:16:58,135
you figure that out, and you have that team

404
00:16:58,135 --> 00:17:00,656
almost like running a ship, and it's autonomous,

405
00:17:00,656 --> 00:17:02,137
and you need to know it, so what happens,

406
00:17:02,137 --> 00:17:04,678
and that's the part where I should have been, this one,

407
00:17:04,678 --> 00:17:07,160
you start introducing other people into your team,

408
00:17:07,160 --> 00:17:10,742
and this can be in very different ways.

409
00:17:10,742 --> 00:17:12,883
Sometimes you inherit people, sometimes you put people

410
00:17:12,883 --> 00:17:14,424
in your team that you don't know.

411
00:17:15,224 --> 00:17:19,748
And it's always a risk because that happens on every team I've known so far.

412
00:17:19,748 --> 00:17:24,212
Like it is in the nature of the thing where you if you even if you know your

413
00:17:24,212 --> 00:17:27,555
team dynamic, figuring out the right people, getting to know the right people

414
00:17:27,555 --> 00:17:30,257
and putting them in the right spot is insanely difficult.

415
00:17:30,257 --> 00:17:33,480
And this will happen, I guarantee, at least in one of your teams.

416
00:17:33,480 --> 00:17:37,683
But the important thing is, you know, that's there.

417
00:17:37,683 --> 00:17:40,966
And then you know that it's it's it's a thing that can happen.

418
00:17:40,966 --> 00:17:42,808
And the way.

419
00:17:43,767 --> 00:17:49,909
I would encourage you is try to counteract it by making sure that the person you're introducing

420
00:17:49,909 --> 00:17:51,890
is definitely a team fit what you feel like.

421
00:17:51,890 --> 00:17:55,871
What we did is we had like an interview where I just made sure, okay, he fits, it's kind

422
00:17:55,871 --> 00:17:56,591
of okay.

423
00:17:56,591 --> 00:18:02,353
But then on top, we had people coming in and I made them go out with the team and I was

424
00:18:02,353 --> 00:18:02,553
like.

425
00:18:02,773 --> 00:18:05,614
really weird dude who was just around the corner

426
00:18:05,614 --> 00:18:08,095
like looking what they're doing, like is it working?

427
00:18:08,095 --> 00:18:08,855
Do they talk?

428
00:18:08,855 --> 00:18:09,935
Is there something going on?

429
00:18:09,935 --> 00:18:12,556
And sometimes you could see like nothing's happening

430
00:18:12,556 --> 00:18:14,576
and you go like, oh, I don't think that fits.

431
00:18:14,576 --> 00:18:16,217
Sometimes the team opened up and started talking.

432
00:18:16,217 --> 00:18:18,617
We just hired one dude who literally just made the team talk

433
00:18:18,617 --> 00:18:21,138
that was like his major attribute and we're like,

434
00:18:21,138 --> 00:18:22,838
they're talking, why are they talking?

435
00:18:22,838 --> 00:18:23,598
They never talk.

436
00:18:23,598 --> 00:18:27,199
I think we should hire this guy.

437
00:18:27,199 --> 00:18:28,099
So you'll figure this out.

438
00:18:28,099 --> 00:18:32,120
And the interesting thing is another thing you can run into

439
00:18:32,120 --> 00:18:32,500
is.

440
00:18:34,462 --> 00:18:37,045
you'll hire people that you like, which you should,

441
00:18:37,045 --> 00:18:39,667
but at the same time, what happens is sometimes

442
00:18:39,667 --> 00:18:41,449
you hire people who like the same soccer team

443
00:18:41,449 --> 00:18:42,550
or like the same drinks you do,

444
00:18:42,550 --> 00:18:47,175
and it becomes too much narrowed down to one specific thing.

445
00:18:47,175 --> 00:18:49,417
So what you wanna do is, and that's why this happens,

446
00:18:49,417 --> 00:18:50,518
is you want to have diversity.

447
00:18:50,518 --> 00:18:53,121
You want to make sure that the group of people

448
00:18:53,121 --> 00:18:56,324
you're hiring is as far spread as possible.

449
00:18:58,625 --> 00:19:02,969
I had like one really weird example that someone on our last team told me on his previous project

450
00:19:02,969 --> 00:19:07,492
where they had no female concept artists or no female in an entire character pipeline.

451
00:19:07,492 --> 00:19:13,458
What happened was during the production they were like done with like a big set of characters,

452
00:19:13,458 --> 00:19:15,099
someone further down the line was like

453
00:19:15,558 --> 00:19:16,819
they look like prostitutes.

454
00:19:16,819 --> 00:19:18,800
I was like, oh shit, you're right.

455
00:19:18,800 --> 00:19:22,003
And you have this entire pipeline.

456
00:19:22,003 --> 00:19:24,505
You spend so much time and money to do this,

457
00:19:24,505 --> 00:19:26,627
and you just realize, oh, crap.

458
00:19:26,627 --> 00:19:29,389
So the more diverse your team is,

459
00:19:29,389 --> 00:19:31,451
and the more different kind of mentalities

460
00:19:31,451 --> 00:19:33,733
you have your team, the more you can counteract these things.

461
00:19:33,733 --> 00:19:35,154
And obviously, we're creating games

462
00:19:35,154 --> 00:19:37,556
to be pleasurable to as many people as possible.

463
00:19:37,556 --> 00:19:40,178
And the more AAA, you get the worse this gets, actually.

464
00:19:40,178 --> 00:19:41,819
So handling that diversity.

465
00:19:42,659 --> 00:19:45,981
with that kind of mentality that you want them to work together,

466
00:19:45,981 --> 00:19:48,902
but you need them not to be the same, leads to this.

467
00:19:48,902 --> 00:19:51,283
Anyways, like it always will lead to these problems.

468
00:19:51,283 --> 00:19:52,444
So you'll have it.

469
00:19:52,444 --> 00:19:55,205
Know your team so you can fix it really fast,

470
00:19:55,205 --> 00:19:59,027
because it can cost time and money big time.

471
00:19:59,027 --> 00:20:02,308
And coming to my last point, this one

472
00:20:02,308 --> 00:20:04,209
is kind of summarizing all of it.

473
00:20:04,209 --> 00:20:04,949
I truly believe that.

474
00:20:08,862 --> 00:20:11,783
all of the points before boiled down to

475
00:20:11,783 --> 00:20:12,764
please leave your ego at home.

476
00:20:12,764 --> 00:20:15,525
And this is easier said than done

477
00:20:15,525 --> 00:20:17,206
because we're all human beings

478
00:20:17,206 --> 00:20:20,027
and you feel pimp if you're leading a lot of people

479
00:20:20,027 --> 00:20:22,288
because the bigger the team got,

480
00:20:22,288 --> 00:20:24,189
the more responsibility you have,

481
00:20:24,189 --> 00:20:27,011
the further you float, the more detached you are,

482
00:20:27,011 --> 00:20:28,351
the prouder you get, right?

483
00:20:28,351 --> 00:20:30,492
Like, oh, look what I'm leading there.

484
00:20:30,492 --> 00:20:31,253
And.

485
00:20:32,034 --> 00:20:36,155
you're like proud about this, you're engaged about it, but you're vain about it as well.

486
00:20:36,155 --> 00:20:40,317
And some people, as I mentioned, have the imposter syndrome and they cover it by just

487
00:20:40,317 --> 00:20:45,258
adding more people into the pool and doing weird things with that. And so what happens at that

488
00:20:45,258 --> 00:20:51,080
point, it's the negative effect I mentioned before where it backfires heavily. So...

489
00:20:53,370 --> 00:20:58,912
The thing is, when you have your ego, and that's the worst part about my presentation,

490
00:20:58,912 --> 00:21:04,553
all of the rules I just stated and things I mentioned, you have to break them constantly

491
00:21:04,553 --> 00:21:06,633
without you wanting to break them.

492
00:21:06,633 --> 00:21:11,074
But sometimes there's a situation that comes up and you realize, oh shit, I need to micromanage

493
00:21:11,074 --> 00:21:12,174
this because it doesn't work.

494
00:21:12,174 --> 00:21:16,175
You don't want to, but sometimes, for example, you have a team that you give them ownership

495
00:21:16,175 --> 00:21:18,736
but they just can't handle it at that point because they're not ready for it.

496
00:21:19,076 --> 00:21:22,038
So you have to go down and just help them to get into this.

